[SLIDE: Research Question]
ALI:
Prior research has linked caffeine to depression and mortality at the individual level, but almost all of it is within one country. We wanted to test whether those patterns hold across countries, and whether they survive controlling for confounders like GDP, smoking, and alcohol. This is an inference project — we're testing whether a relationship exists and how robust it is.

[SLIDE: Data Overview]
BRANDON:
We merged seven datasets into a country-year panel. Coffee and tea consumption from World Population Review were converted into estimated daily caffeine per capita. For outcomes, we used IHME GBD data on depression and all-cause mortality. For confounders: GDP per capita, smoking, and alcohol from Our World in Data. One caveat — our caffeine variable is a cross-sectional estimate applied across multiple years.

[SLIDE: Data Wrangling]
BRANDON:
Wrangling involved scraping HTML tables for beverage data, standardizing country names across sources, and filtering out regional aggregates from the GBD exports. We saved a full panel and a most-recent-year cross-section, both reproducible from our checkpoint notebooks.

[SLIDE: EDA — Temporal Coverage]
ANCHIT:
We checked data coverage first. Depression and mortality go back to the 1990s; smoking and alcohol are narrower. When we stratified trends by caffeine tercile, high-caffeine countries showed consistently lower mortality — but they're also wealthier European countries. So we can't tell yet if it's caffeine or GDP.

[SLIDE: EDA — Distributions]
ANCHIT:
Coffee and tea consumption are right-skewed — a handful of Northern European countries consume far more than the global median. Caffeine inherits that skewness, so we used medians throughout. Mortality distributions shifted leftward over time, meaning countries improved. Depression stayed relatively stable.

[SLIDE: EDA — Bivariate Associations]
CESAR:
Cross-sectionally, higher caffeine countries have significantly lower mortality. That correlation is consistent across years, not just one snapshot. But the caffeine-depression link is weaker and less consistent. And the critical finding: GDP correlates strongly with both caffeine and mortality — the obvious alternative explanation.

[SLIDE: EDA — Confounder Structure]
CESAR:
The correlation heatmap confirms the confounding structure. When we stratified by GDP tercile, the caffeine-outcome association weakened within each group compared to the overall pattern. This told us regression adjustment was essential.

[SLIDE: Analysis — Regression Results]
ANCHIT or JOHN:
We ran three OLS models on the 2020 cross-section — 124 countries. For mortality, the unadjusted caffeine coefficient was minus 99 per 100,000, highly significant at p equals 0.0009. After adding GDP, it dropped 62 percent to minus 37, p equals 0.041. Fully adjusted — adding smoking and alcohol — it fell to minus 35, p equals 0.057, just outside conventional significance. So the raw association is mostly a GDP effect, though a small residual signal may remain.

For depression, caffeine was non-significant in every model. Our sensitivity analysis showed coefficients were stable under plus or minus 25 percent variation in caffeine conversion factors.

[SLIDE: Limitations]
JOHN:
Key limitations: this is ecological — country-level patterns say nothing about individuals. Our caffeine estimate is approximate. And the data is more reliable for wealthier nations, which could inflate associations.

[SLIDE: Ethics]
ALI:
Ecological correlations cannot support causal claims about individuals. Caffeine consumption is culturally embedded — tea ceremonies, coffee culture, traditional qahwa — and we should not frame any pattern as better or worse.

[SLIDE: Conclusions]
ALI:
Bottom line: country-level caffeine shows a negative association with mortality, but it's largely explained by GDP. After full adjustment, the signal is borderline at p equals 0.057. The depression association is null. These patterns are consistent with prior literature but the ecological design means they're suggestive, not confirmatory. Thanks for watching.

